    <text>
        <front>
            <div type="abstract">
                <p tid="1">Canonical aspiration and dedication prayers to conclude the Compendium of Dhāraṇīs (Toh 1094-1108).</p>
            </div>
        </front>
        <body>
            <div type="article">
                <head type="article" tid="4">Aspiration</head>
                <div type="section" xml:id="O1JC114941JC20569-article-1">
                    <milestone unit="chunk" xml:id="EFT-KB-DHARANIS-KANGYUR-SECTION-1"/>
                    <p tid="8">Fifteen works that bring the Dhāraṇī section to a conclusion with aspiration prayers, dedication, and expressions of auspiciousness.</p>
                    <milestone unit="chunk" xml:id="EFT-KB-DHARANIS-KANGYUR-SECTION-101"/>
                    <p tid="9">Most of these works are extracts from longer texts found elsewhere in the Kangyur, and all but two are themselves duplicated, as well, in
                        other Kangyur sections. </p>
                    <milestone unit="chunk" xml:id="O1JC114941JC20569-3"/>
                    <p tid="10">Of the two works that are not duplicates of works elsewhere in the
                        Kangyur, the <title xml:lang="en">Prayer of Maitreya</title> (<title xml:lang="Bo-Ltn">byams pa’i smon lam</title>, Toh 1096) is 
                        excerpted from <title xml:lang="en">
                            <ref target="https://read.84000.co/translation/toh85.html">The Question of Maitreya (1)</ref>
                        </title> 
                        (<title xml:lang="Sa-Ltn">Maitreya­paripṛcchā</title>, Toh 85) in the Heap of Jewels section, and only <title xml:lang="en">The Prayer of
                            Sublime Action</title> (<title xml:lang="Bo-Ltn">mchog gi spyod pa’i smon lam</title>, Toh 1097), is a text entirely unique to this section.</p>
                    <milestone unit="chunk" xml:id="O1JC114941JC20569-4"/>
                    <p tid="11">There is another set of aspiration and dedication prayers found in the Degé Kangyur in a 
                        <ref target="https://read.84000.co/section/O1JC114941JC21416.html">Dedication-aspiration</ref> 
                        subdivision at the end of the Tantra Collection 
                        (<foreign xml:lang="Bo-Ltn">rgyud ’bum</foreign>), Toh 809–827. In Kangyurs of the Themphangma lineage, there is also a group of
                    aspiration and dedication prayers at the end of the Discipline (Vinaya) section.</p>
                </div>
